	   <tr><td colspan=2>I believe when the game was created the implementation of languages should have included the LACK of the ability to talk to other races.&nbsp;&nbsp;<br><br>In other words, there would be no Common Tongue, just your racial tongue.  Upon beginning your character you would be able to speak only with your fellow elves if you chose a wood elf for instance.  Perhaps, even High Elves wouldn't be able to communicate with Wood Elves, and Ogres couldn't talk to Trolls and make themselves understood.<br><br>To facilitate the learning of other race's tongues<br>you would have to utilize the  /em  or emotes to make basic contact or buy the skill from your guildleader and practice on your newfound friends.  The skill would rise just as any skill in EQ rises with use giving the "Master" rating an actual context within the game.  A skill level of "Poor" might make a sentence such as:<br><br>"The troll went to go buy his level 9 spells." to something like this this:<br><br>"Tje trill wont to ga by kis lavul 9 sbylls" which MIGHT be understood if you knew the context in which it was spoken, but would be confusing to anyone else.<br><br>Imagine meeting a different race and communicating through shrugs, pointing, scowls, etc etc!  The choice of your character would become very important indeed!<br><br>This approach would give the language skill a function instead of the "nice to have, but basically useless" skill that we have in its' present form.<br><br>My two cents, anyways...<br>Good luck, young shammy trolls, wherever you may roam!<br>&nbsp;<br>Emperor and Shamanic High Priest of the Trolls<br>"Worship Innoruuk, you worthless cattle!"<br></td></tr>
