<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%>
	   <a name=971807969806></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f971807969806><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=9&mid=971807969806>Nasty Dueling Tricks for the Lower Levels</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=9&mid=971807969806#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=2076><span id=Sage>Pusbag</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>1378 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Oct 17th 2:39 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.75]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>This is by no means a complete guide to the art of putting the smack down on your fellow players, but they are what I have discovered effective methods when you have the itch that needs scratching-- tougher game than that goblin or orc you've been waling on for the past two weeks.<br>Let's get to it, shall we?<br><br>MELEE TYPES<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;When fighting the melee classes engage them at max range.    If you attempt to go toe-to-toe with them you are playing to their strength, so utilize your magical abilities.    Cast Flash of Light (FoL) on them and cast your Damage over Time (DoT) spells on them.    Recast as necessary as the DoTs wear off.    After you have FoL/DoTted them, run to a safe place and med.       Wait for the chat line message to let you know when your DoT has worn off-- especially Sicken, as it prevents their natural regeneration from allowing them to heal-- then go reapply, rinse, repeat!    Blinding them prevents them from seeing where you stole off to to get some mana back and keeps them from running up to you to engage you in some hand-to-gland fighting.      If possible, when in a zone with a body of water, cast "Levitate" and engage them at the water's edge.    Move back out over the water and cast away.    If they come out to get you, move back and BLAST 'IM!    There is nothing funnier than watching a melee type floundering in the water looking for his corpse wondering where he died.    Then you can make some coin by charging him to go get his body using "Enduring Breath".    Lol   :D     If it is imperative you must fight up close "Drowsy" first then move in.    But avoid this if possible.<br><br>CASTER TYPES<br>Ok, back at it...  against casters in general you want to close in and engage them up close and personal, hand-to-gland so to speak.    Cast away in between swings with Sicken to stop their health regeneration, add TB (Tuberculosis?!?  Could be...  ;)  ) and use your best DD spell on them as they won't have many health points most likely.  Put them down as quickly as possible since they have the ability to out-nuke you.  Your hitting them will interupt their casting and save you health points.  Remember to save your "Bash" for the moment they begin casting.  Do NOT use the "press the button whenever it lights up" technique, but time it wisely it keep them off balance.    If they are casters with pets throw a FoL on the pet to get it running away (it acts as a "fear" spell), then focus solely on the caster.    Ignore their pet and kill the owner!     Now, if it is an Enchanter cast Sicken on YOURSELF so that he can't mez you.    Cure poison breaks their Tashani spell on you too.    If the victim is a Cleric or Paladin have "Cure Blindness" memmed since they use FoL too and remember which rune or hotkey it is under.  You don't want to be in the same boat as your intended victim, do you?  Chances are, he won't have it memmed, so when you cast FoL, then "Cure Blindness", he wont be ready for it.  Now take him out.<br>  Remember one of the advantages of a shammy is that ALL of our DoTs stack-- yes, ALL of them-- so as you level up continue to utilize older ones when you duel.<br>  If worse comes to worse, run (you are SoWed, aren't you?) or gate out into another place in the zone you are dueling.    Heal, med, get back to the job at hand-- killing your enemy.<br>Ok, take these next tricks with a grain of salt and remember I am a troll after all (evil, remember?).    There is a rumored bug that prevents spells taking effect on you when you are standing knee deep in water.    The caster will see on his chat screen that his spells are having an effect on you when in reality they are not.      He wastes all his mana on destroying you, then BOOM!    You attack!    If you are really bent, run to a higher level mob (SoWed of coarse) run back to your foe and "Gate".    It kinda forces the issue...    I only recommend this technique for those individuals who insist on you sharing the camp you have worked so long and hard to split or insist on KSing you with high DD spells.    Lol.    Ok, it IS only a game after all!   :D     Not that I would condone these ideas...<br>Alright, what next?    Remember some classes have trouble wearing all that pretty armor and maintaining their weight so "Disempower" works well to lower their AGI and STR stats, especially if they are close to the upper limits.    Do an inspection before your duel to check.<br>  "Drowsy" is resisted less than "Walking Sleep" at the lower levels.<br>  Using "Levitate" in the overhead view camera position to place your self above your enemy and cast on them is amusing after you FoL them, run away and they stop swinging to prevent the "Your target is out of range" spam message.    Re-FoL them to keep them from seeing you run up on them.     Just make sure you remain above them or they will see you. <br>   You'll notice I use FoL a lot.     This is probably THE most underused duelling spell in the game.    It is very demoralizing to be blind for 2-3 minutes and suddenly be able to see and realize that while you have been blind your friendly shammy has been DoTting you half to death, not to mention the wandering mob that aggroed on you while you waited to peer at the world like a newborn kitten, anxiously wondering what has been happening to you.     Very effective.<br>   If you are fighting in the Freeport area don't hesitate to utilize the secret entrances to the undergound to get some breathing space.    And, yes, you can cast on your opponent in there too!<br>When you are able, cast "Inner Fire" on yourself to heal as it is twice as effective manawise as your "Heal" spells.<br>  Utilizing "Levitate" in hilly areas is effective against larger melee races in that you can entice them to engage you at the peaks, you run to the valleys and cast on them to pull them down to you.    Additional damage is dealt out to them by falling making your job easier.<br>  Well, for whatever reason the Shammy Strategy section has fewer posts than the other classes.     I aim to change that with what (I hope) are some well thought out and reasoned posts.    I believe the Shaman is one of the more enjoyable classes to play and the troll is the icing on the cake.    So if you are on Druzzil Ro, give me a tell!<br>Good luck, young shammy!<br><br><br>&nbsp;<br>Emperor and Shamanic High Priest of the Trolls<br>"Worship Innoruuk, you worthless cattle!"<br></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
